                                        📚 Database Normalization vs Denormalization
🔹 Normalization

Definition:
Normalization is the process of breaking a large table into smaller, related tables and establishing relationships between them to reduce redundancy.

🎯 Goals:
Minimize redundancy
Avoid data inconsistency
Improve data integrity
Simplify maintenance
⚙️ Concept:
Table (T)
   ↓
T1      T2      T3
(related via keys)
✅ Example:

Before Normalization:

| StudentID | Name | Course | Instructor |
| --------- | ---- | ------ | ---------- |
| 1         | Yash | DBMS   | A          |
| 2         | Ram  | DBMS   | A          |


👉 Instructor repeated → redundancy

After Normalization:

Student Table

| StudentID | Name |
| --------- | ---- |
| 1         | Yash |
| 2         | Ram  |


Course Table

Course	Instructor
DBMS	A
⚠️ Important:
Avoid over-normalization (too many tables → complex joins)
🔹 Denormalization

Definition:
Denormalization is the process of intentionally adding redundancy to improve read performance.

⚙️ Concept:
T1 + T2 + T3
     ↓
   Single Table (T)

🎯 Why Use It?
Improve query performance
Reduce joins
Faster data retrieval
Best for read-heavy systems

✅ Advantages:
Faster queries (no joins needed)
Simpler queries
Better performance in read-intensive apps

❌ Disadvantages:
Redundancy → wastes memory
Data inconsistency risk
Slow updates/writes (update same data in multiple places)
⚠️ Example Problem:

If HR department location is stored in multiple rows:
Update missed in one row → ❌ inconsistent data

Quick Comparison Table
| Feature        | Normalization ✅ | Denormalization ⚡ |
| -------------- | --------------- | ----------------- |
| Redundancy     | Low             | High              |
| Data Integrity | High            | Medium/Low        |
| Query Speed    | Slower (joins)  | Faster            |
| Complexity     | More joins      | Simpler queries   |
| Best Use Case  | OLTP systems    | OLAP / Read-heavy |

🧠 Easy Memory Trick
Normalization = Clean & Organized 🧹
Denormalization = Fast but Messy ⚡
